I stayed at The Logan Hilton Curio Collection Hotel for the first time on my Birthday weekend. I stayed from 3.16.2023 to 3.20.23. During my stay, several mishaps happened. Here's the breakdown: I didn't know upon checking in tht there was a nightly security/incident fee. The person who booked me never mentioned it. The manager let me put 2 nights down so tht helped a little to ease up my funds. Then my rooms thermostat wasnt heating up the room so they had to switch my room in the middle of the night. Then, the new room had mold/dirt in the refrigerator so they gave me a new fridge. THEN, the Spa thts in the hotel mixed up my dates BUT they were able to fit me in abd gave me a few services tht normally you have to pay for. I also got a discount fir the mixup. I say all that to say this... with ALL the mixups and hiccups that happened, I was accommodated so well and received A1 treatment the whole time. The staff has the BEST bedside manner I've ever encountered. The rooms were clean, well stocked with all the needed necessities and there was no weird smells or noise at all. There are many things to do thts inside the hotel like swimming, gym, breakfast cafe and several restaurants and bars. All amazing places. How they train their staff is amazing, I was highly impressed. I even booked an extra night and was given my same rate with no incidental fee. The Logan is definitely an A1 hotel with Grade A service and staff to be there for you. Thts more important then anything else. How they treat you when things go wrong, they take accountability and immediately fix it. Its a beautiful atmospheric hotel on the parkway. It's definitely a revisit for me ‚ù§Ô∏è.

Logan Square (also known as Logan Circle) is one of the five original squares mapped by William Penn, founder if Philadelphia.

The centerpiece if the Square is the Swan Fountain by Alexander Stirling Calder. It's a beautiful fountain that looks especially nice when illuminated at night. In the summer, the fountain attracts children looking for a place to cool off.

The neighborhood features a high-end hotel, restaurants for every taste and budget, and a number if outstanding museums.

From Logan Square, you can see City Hall at one end of the Parkway and the Philadelphia Museum of Art at the other end. It's a pretty area with plenty to see and do.

Most of us pass through on our way to the library or something and because there's so much traffic around it and we're walking through it because that's the most expedient route somewhere, of course we stop noticing it. But I do like when I see tourists appreciating it. Fun fact, the Alexander Calder sculptures of the Native American figures in the fountain represent the three major rivers of Philly. The girl leaning on her side against the ticked-off swan represents Wissahickon Creek, the woman holding the neck of a swan stands for the Schuylkill River, and the male with the pike spouting water over his head represents the Delaware.
